pouch boundary-line patch 0018 - poll()/select() readiness over /net (net-6b-3)

NET-DESIGN.md section 12.2; closes the net-5 SOCK_NONBLOCK -> EOPNOTSUPP
poll-readiness seam. net-5 (0016) and net-6a-2 (0017) made the AF_INET
socket calls (connect/send/recv/shutdown/...) work over netd's /net 9P
files, but poll()/select() over a /net socket fd were still wrong: the
0015 tag-dispatch shim translates a tagged socket fd to the slot's
kernel_fd, which for an AF_INET slot is the /net/<proto>/N/data fd -- a
REGULAR dev9p file. The kernel dev9p.poll slot (net-6b-2b) treats a
regular 9P file as POSIX always-ready (it probes only a Spoor whose qid
carries QTPOLL), so polling the data fd reports ready unconditionally and
defeats the wait: a poll(POLLIN) returns immediately instead of blocking
until data, and select()-style multiplexing reports every /net fd ready
always.

This STACKS on 0015 (the poll tag-dispatch) + 0016 (the AF_INET family) +
0006 (the slot table). It adds NO kernel surface: the only new operation
is a SYS_open of the readiness file (read/write/close + SYS_poll are all
already seamed; ARCH 11.5's zero-socket-syscalls commitment holds).

The mechanism: netd serves a per-connection readiness file
/net/<proto>/N/ready whose qid carries the reserved 9P bit QTPOLL
(net-6b-2a/2b). dev9p.poll probes ONLY a QTPOLL Spoor; a SYS_poll on it
issues a non-consuming readiness Tread (offset = the event mask) that the
#841 elected reader drives, returning the satisfied revents (POLLIN/
POLLOUT/POLLERR/POLLHUP) without consuming data. So the pouch poll() must
target the ready sibling, not the data fd. A NEW slot helper resolves the
poll target:

  pouch_sock_poll_fd(fd)
    UNTAGGED fd        -> fd unchanged (poll a raw kernel handle).
    FAM_UNIX tagged fd -> the slot's kernel_fd (the /srv byte stream,
                          pollable via the kernel devsrv .poll slot) --
                          the 0015 behavior, unchanged.
    FAM_INET tagged fd -> the /net/<proto>/N/ready fd, opened lazily on
                          the first poll and held for the socket's
                          lifetime (closed at close()). -1 (POLLNVAL) if
                          the slot is vacant or the ready file cannot be
                          opened.

The poll() shim (src/select/poll.c) routes its tagged-fd dispatch through
pouch_sock_poll_fd instead of pouch_sock_kernel_fd; the caller's pollfd
.events (POLLIN/POLLOUT) pass straight through -- the kernel threads them
to dev9p.poll as the Tread offset, and netd's check_ready reads them as
the requested mask (POLLIN=0x001/POLLOUT=0x004 align across pouch, the
kernel, and netd). select()/pselect()/ppoll() inherit the fix: they all
route through poll() (0005). The readiness fd lifecycle is reset at slot
alloc and torn down at close(), alongside the ctl fd; a peer thread
poll()ing the SAME fd or a close racing the lazy open is reconciled under
the slot lock (keep one ready fd, close the loser), matching the inherited
single-user-per-socket discipline.

Invariants (NET-DESIGN.md section 15.1 -- composes existing section-28
invariants, adds none): I-1/I-23/I-28 (a Proc reaches only the /net its
territory grants); I-5 (netd owns the NIC; pouch never touches hardware);
I-9 (the readiness wake is the dev9p.poll register-then-observe -- the
kernel half, net_poll.tla). The pouch side carries no wait/wake state of
its own: it opens the ready fd and parks in SYS_poll, exactly like any
other pollable object.

Files (all stack on the post-0017 tree):
  src/internal/_pouch_socket.h   the ready_fd slot field + pouch_sock_poll_fd
                                 decl + the now-true poll coverage note.
  src/network/_pouch_socket.c    reset ready_fd at alloc; close it at close;
                                 the pouch_sock_poll_fd helper (lazy open).
  src/select/poll.c              route tagged-fd dispatch through
                                 pouch_sock_poll_fd; update the header doc.

Binding design: NET-DESIGN.md section 12.2; docs/reference/121-netd.md (the
net-6b kernel half) + docs/reference/78-pouch.md (the AF_INET backend).
Invariants P-1, P-3, P-4. Proving binary: /pouch-hello-net -- extended with
the deterministic poll() control surface over a connected /net socket
(POLLOUT-ready on a writable socket; POLLIN times out with no data; both
